Organization = {{Amer Water Resources Assoc; Univ Alaska Fairbanks Water \& Environm Res
   Ctr; Alaska Power \& Tel Co; BP Explorat; GW Sci; Harza Engn Co;
   Meridian Management Inc; Montgomery Watson; Oasis Environm Inc; Remote
   Utilities Syst Grp}},
Abstract = {{Pre- and post-burn stream discharge was monitored between 1983 and 1999
   in adjacent catchments: Tharp's Creek, an intermittent stream, and Log
   Creek, a perennial stream, in Sequoia National Park Tharp's Creek
   catchment (0.13 km(2)) was treated with a prescribed fire in 1990. Log
   Creek catchment (0.50 km(2)) served as the control. Prior to the burn,
   Tharp's Creek flowed an average of 195 days yr(-1) but, in years with
   below normal precipitation, measurable flow occurred on average 150 days
   yr(-1) (n=5). After the burn days with measurable flow increased to 255
   days yr(-1) for all years (n=9) and to 225 days yr(-1) in years with
   below normal precipitation (n=4). Annual runoff coefficients in Tharp's
   Creek prior to the burn ranged from 0.005 to 0.20 during dry years and
   from 0.30 to 0.55 during wet years. Runoff coefficients in the Log Creek
   catchment ranged from 0.20 to 0.48 during dry years and from 0.60 to
   0.80 during wet years. After the fire, runoff increased significantly in
   Tharp's Creek with coefficients of 0.10 to 0.70 during dry years and
   0.35 to 0.80 during wet years. In the control catchment, Log Creek,
   runoff did not increase significantly in the post-fire period. Post-burn
   increases in runoff at Tharp's Creek watershed were correlated with
   postburn tree mortality which decreased evapo-transpiration and reduced
   canopy interception of precipitation.}},
